  "answer": "**The only Iqbal poem in the corpus that refers to childhood explicitly is \"Ehd-e-Tifli\" (\"The Age of Childhood\") from *Bang-E-Dara Part 1* (Chapter 19).**[^1]\n\nThis short reflective poem evokes the poet's own early years, portraying the world as seen through a child's innocent eyes. Key explicit references include the title itself—\"The Age of Childhood\"—and the line \"Though childhood's pain at times would make me weep\" (describing minor hardships like the sound of a door chain rattling). The full poem continues with imagery of staring at the moon, asking naive questions, and possessing \"pure, inquiring thought\" rather than a fully formed heart.[^2]\n\nNo other poems by Allama Iqbal (across *Bang-E-Dara* Parts 1, 2, or 3) mention \"childhood\" explicitly in their English translations. While several poems feature children as subjects or speakers—such as \"Bachay Ki Dua\" (\"A Child's Prayer,\" Chapter 16), \"Bacha aur Shama\" (\"A Child and a Moth,\" Chapter 15), or \"Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet\" (\"Hindustani Children's National Song,\" Chapter 26)—they do not reference the concept or period of *childhood* directly.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 19: \"Ehd-e-Tifli\" [chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/19-ehd-e-tifli/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, Chapter 19: \"Ehd-e-Tifli\" [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/19-ehd-e-tifli/translation/#p-4e88ba).\n\n[^3]: Derived from full chapter listings for Iqbal's works in the corpus; English search confirmed no other \"childhood\" matches.",
